  "prompt": "What are the advantages of mean, median, and mode?",
  "response": "Here's a comparison of the advantages of mean, median, and mode:\n\nMean:\n1. Uses all data points\n2. Most commonly used measure of central tendency\n3. Algebraically manipulatable\n4. Good for normally distributed data\n5. Precise mathematical representation\n\nMedian:\n1. Not affected by extreme outliers\n2. Better for skewed distributions\n3. Represents the middle value\n4. More robust in datasets with significant variations\n5. Useful for ordinal data\n\nMode:\n1. Best for categorical data\n2. Shows most frequent value\n3. Can identify peaks in distribution\n4. Works well with non-numeric data\n5. Simple to calculate\n\nSpecific advantages:\nMean:\n- Precise calculation\n- Useful in statistical analysis\n- Reflects entire dataset's characteristics\n\nMedian:\n- Resistant to extreme values\n- Represents central point in ordered data\n- More representative in uneven distributions\n\nMode:\n- Easily interpretable\n- Shows most common occurrence\n- Useful in frequency-based analyses\n\nEach measure has unique strengths depending on data type and distribution, so choosing the appropriate measure depends on specific context and research goals.",
